tweet: @PandaValue Given how good the balance sheet is and cheap funding, as you mentioned, they've got a lot of time. I've been long-time bearish/short on $CBL and $WPG because they didn't have access to capital. I wouldn't short $SPG though because of its great credit rating.

tweet: @irbezek And I have a somewhat crazy, but not entirely illogical thought that $SPG could be an acquisition target by a consortium of sovereign wealth funds or even $BRK.B - though it would be universally hated. But Buffett is familiar with the business given he owns $SRG personally.

tweet: @irbezek There are a few markers out there with GGP and Westfield that PMV are higher. I think $SPG cut a pretty daggum good deal to get $TCO. They are doubling down on enclosed malls.

name: Panda Value
tweet: The bond market doesn't see this as a distressed asset, but the equity market is implying significant impairments. I couldn't disagree more. In 2021, I plan on making $SPG a core holding within my portfolio. I see this as a 10-12% return investment over the coming years.

name: Panda Value
tweet: There is much fear and angst about the "death of the mall," but I think this is largely overblown for America's preeminent malls (i.e. $SPG). The debt markets agree. $SPG just raised $800M of 7-yr notes at 1.75% and $700M of 10-yr notes at 2.2%.

name: Panda Value
tweet: Even if the mall does go away, the real estate the mall sits on is irreplaceable, which is why $SPG is aggressively investing in their malls, taking back boxes and enhancing the ecosystem with new stores, hotels, apartments, restaurants.

name: Panda Value
tweet: $SPG is a security that I believe is totally mispriced and currently is a 2.5% position for me. It would have been bigger, but I saw better opportunities in 2020. In 2021, not so much.
